 I laid myself down, flat. My eyes fixed on the road in front of my house. It lit under the gold light from the lamps inside. They don't know I'm here. I locked my room and came here. Sleep was a rare thing now. When it came it was long and calm. Refreshing. But more than few times it was short and terrifying. I often woke with sweat down my brow and a blurry vision, no....I started calling them what they were now- memories. Memories of a woman who abandoned her child. I felt him. suffocating, freezing as waters filled his lungs and stomach. The bamboo basket rode the crashing waves striking every protruding rock it could. The boy shivered, his small delicate fingers holding tight to the cloth he was wrapped in. Eyes closed because they were still heavy to open. And he was scared of what he''ll see. The cries echoed in the night and he almost fell in the river. I had seen this dream so many times before. And every time before, I felt sympathy for the infant and questioned the woman who left him. I wanted to help both of them. But knowing it was me all along! Knowing she was my mother who stood on the banks watching as I was about to die, made it completely different. }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
